article.description: A funny thing happened Tuesday night at the MCI Center: Chamique Holdsclaw sat down, yet the Mystics kept scoring.
article.headline: Holdsclaw gets rest and double-double
article.linkText: Mystics hand Silver Spurs seventh straight loss
article.story:
WASHINGTON (AP) -- A funny thing happened Tuesday night at the
MCI Center: Chamique Holdsclaw sat down, yet the Washington Mystics
kept scoring.

Holdsclaw took a break for the first time with 3:55 remaining in
the first half and the score tied. By halftime, the Mystics had
built an eight-point lead and were on their way to a 76-60 victory
over the slumping San Antonio Silver Stars.

"Coach took me out and he was going to put me back in,"
Holdsclaw said. "I was like, 'Let me rest my legs!' And the bench
came in and played with energy. That's what this team needs. When
people step on the court, they've got to bring it."

Holdsclaw finished with 24 points and 10 rebounds, but she
didn't have to carry a lopsided share of the load for a change.
Stacey Dales-Schumann, who matched her season-high with 12 points,
and Murriel Page led the surge late in the first half.

The Mystics have won two straight, their first winning streak of
the season, and this was their first victory of the season by more
than two points. The Mystics (4-5) also improved to 2-4 at home,
but their other "home" victory came when they were displaced by a
Madonna concert and had to play at the Comcast Center in Maryland.

"You just don't know how good it feels to actually win in this
building," first-year coach Michael Adams said.

Marie Ferdinand scored 12 points -- shooting just 2-for-11 from
the field but making all eight free throws -- to lead the Silver
Stars (3-8), who set a franchise record with their seventh
consecutive loss.

"We've got to keep working," coach Dee Brown said.
"Everything gets solved on the court. We've got a veteran team,
but it's young enough to keep it exciting."

Neither team led by more than six points until Dales-Schumann
made three consecutive baskets to end the first half, giving the
Mystics a 41-33 lead. Washington finished the 11-0 run early in the
second half.

San Antonio cut a 14-point lead to six in the second half after
7-foot-2 Margo Dydek entered the game and went on a tear. Dydek
scored nine points and grabbed six rebounds in 14 minutes, but
Holdsclaw rallied with two baskets in a 10-3 run to put the Mystics
back in control.
